    </li>
    <li>
        Canyon sections above the hatchery.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    This river fishes well even after light rain, making it a good choice during stormy weeks.
</p>
<h2>
   Fishing Regulations in Oregon &amp; Washington
</h2>
<p>
    Before you go, be sure to check both Oregon and Washington fishing regulations, especially since you may be fishing in both states.
</p>
<h3>
    Things You’ll Need:
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oregon/Washington angling license</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Harvest tags for steelhead</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Barbless hooks</strong> in some areas
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Always differentiate between <strong>wild steelhead</strong> (must be released) and <strong>hatchery fish</strong> (marked with a clipped adipose fin), which you can often retain.
</p>
